          <h2>How &amp; Where to Pay Each Fee</h2>
          <div class="payment-grid">
            <div class="pg-item">
              <div class="pg-fee">I-130 — $675</div>
              <div class="pg-where"><strong>Where:</strong> USCIS — check/MO payable to "U.S. Department of Homeland Security" or online at my.uscis.gov</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pg-item">
              <div class="pg-fee">NVC fee — $325</div>
              <div class="pg-where"><strong>Where:</strong> ceac.state.gov — credit/debit card after NVC sends invoice. Usually 1–4 weeks after USCIS approval.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pg-item">
              <div class="pg-fee">Medical exam — varies</div>
              <div class="pg-where"><strong>Where:</strong> Directly to the USCIS-approved panel physician in the beneficiary's country. Cash or local payment methods.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pg-item">
              <div class="pg-fee">USCIS Immigrant Fee — $220</div>
              <div class="pg-where"><strong>Where:</strong> pay.gov — credit/debit card online, within 1 year of entry. Do this in the first few days after arriving.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pg-item">
              <div class="pg-fee">I-751 — $750</div>
              <div class="pg-where"><strong>Where:</strong> USCIS — check/MO or online through my.uscis.gov. File during months 21–24 before conditional card expires.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="content-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
          <div class="faq-list">
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>How much does a CR-1 visa cost in 2026?</summary>
              <p>Approximately $2,220 in required government fees: I-130 ($675) + NVC immigrant visa fee ($325) + USCIS Immigrant Fee ($220) + I-751 to remove conditions ($750) + one medical exam (~$250 average). With optional attorney fees and translations, most couples spend $3,500–$7,000 total from petition to 10-year green card.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is the I-130 filing fee?</summary>
              <p>$675 as of 2026, paid by the U.S. citizen or LPR petitioner to USCIS. Non-refundable. Form I-130A (beneficiary supplement) is submitted with the I-130 at no additional cost. Pay by check or money order when mailing, or by credit/debit card when filing online through my.uscis.gov.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is the NVC immigrant visa fee?</summary>
              <p>$325, paid by the beneficiary online through ceac.state.gov after the case is transferred from USCIS to NVC. This covers the consular interview scheduling and visa processing. It is separate from the $675 I-130 filing fee and must be paid before the NVC will begin collecting documents.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Is CR-1 cheaper than K-1?</summary>
              <p>Yes — significantly. CR-1 costs ~$2,220 in government fees vs. ~$3,680 for K-1. The main savings come from not needing an I-485 Adjustment of Status ($1,440 saved) and requiring only one medical exam instead of two ($200–$500 saved). With attorney fees, total CR-1 savings are typically $1,500–$3,000 compared to K-1.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>What is the USCIS Immigrant Fee?</summary>
              <p>$220 paid online at pay.gov after the CR-1 beneficiary enters the U.S. It must be paid within one year of entry. This fee triggers USCIS to produce and mail the green card (Form I-551) to your U.S. address. Without it, your green card will not be sent even if you entered legally on the CR-1 visa.</p>
            </details>
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>Do I need two medical exams on the CR-1 path?</summary>
              <p>No — only one. The CR-1 beneficiary has one medical exam by a panel physician in their home country before the consular interview. Unlike K-1, there is no second I-693 medical exam after entry because CR-1 beneficiaries enter directly as permanent residents without filing for Adjustment of Status.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </section>

